A x B = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 2), (2, 3)}

Now, let's calculate the Cartesian product of B and A, denoted as B x A.

B x A = {(2, 1), (2, 2), (3, 1), (3, 2)}

Now, we will find the symmetric difference of the two resulting sets, (A x B) and (B x A). The symmetric difference of two sets is the set of elements which are in either of the sets, but not in their intersection.

Symmetric Difference (A x B, B x A) = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 2), (2, 3), (2, 1), (3, 1), (3, 2)} - {(2, 2)}

Symmetric Difference (A x B, B x A) = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 3), (2, 1), (3, 1), (3, 2)}

Now, let's find the symmetric difference of (B x A) and (A x B).

Symmetric Difference (B x A, A x B) = {(2, 1), (2, 2), (3, 1), (3, 2), (1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 2), (2, 3)} - {(2, 2)}

Symmetric Difference (B x A, A x B) = {(2, 1), (3, 1), (3, 2), (1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 3)}

We can see that the symmetric difference of (A x B) and (B x A) is the same as the symmetric difference of (B x A) and (A x B). Therefore, the symmetric difference of two sets is commutative with respect to the Cartesian product.
